"Mejía-Centeno I., Martínez-Hernández A., Fuentes G.A.","Effect of low-sulfur fuels upon NH3 and N2O emission during operation of commercial three-way catalytic converters",2007,"Topics in Catalysis","42-43","1-4",,"381","385",,,10.1007/s11244-007-0210-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34347379181&partnerID=40&md5=eae46572be1638f7799ed008c78c0f07","Área de Ingeniería Química, Universidad A. Metropolitana-Iztapalapa, México, D.F., 09340, Mexico","Mejía-Centeno, I., Área de Ingeniería Química, Universidad A. Metropolitana-Iztapalapa, México, D.F., 09340, Mexico; Martínez-Hernández, A., Área de Ingeniería Química, Universidad A. Metropolitana-Iztapalapa, México, D.F., 09340, Mexico; Fuentes, G.A., Área de Ingeniería Química, Universidad A. Metropolitana-Iztapalapa, México, D.F., 09340, Mexico","The use of low-sulfur fuel is known to improve the performance of the three-way catalytic converter (TWC). However, in this work we report how low-sulfur operation of commercial TWC also favors formation of N2O and NH3 as by products. We found that low-sulfur rich operation above 300°C increases the production of NH3, inhibiting the formation of N2O characteristic of high-sulfur operation. During lean operation, the production of N2O near the stoichiometric point is not significantly affected by the sulfur level. The large production of N2O observed during light-off is not affected by SO2 when the operation is lean, but under rich conditions N2O is produced up to 575°C. The increased production of NH3 and N2O in TWC as a result of the introduction of low-sulfur gasoline is an area that requires further analysis because of its implication upon public health in large urban settings. © 2007 Springer Science+Business Media, LLC.","Global warming; Low sulfur gasoline; N2O; NH3; TWC",,,,,,,"Kašpar, J., Fornasiero, P., Hickey, N., (2003) Catal. Today, 77, p. 419; Kaufmann, T.G., Kaldor, A., Stuntz, G.F., Kerby, M.C., Ansell, L.L., (2000) Catal. Today, 62, p. 77; Kean, A.J., Harley, R.A., Littlejohn, D., Kendall, G.R., (2000) Environ. Sci. Technol, 34, p. 3535; Pierson, W.R., Brachaczek, W.W., (1983) Environ. Sci. Technol, 17, p. 757; Fraser, M.P., Cass, G.R., (1998) Environ. Sci. Technol, 32, p. 1053; Baum, M.M., Kiyomiya, E.S., Kumar, S., Lappas, A.M., Kapinus, V.A., Lord III, H.C., (2001) Environ. Sci. Technol, 35, p. 3735; E.L. Glover, M. Cumberworth, EPA 420-R-03-001 (Mobile-6.1 Particulate emission factor model)Pérez-Ramírez, J., Kapteijn, F., Schöffel, K., Moulijn, J.A., (2003) Appl. Catal. B: Environ, 44, p. 117; Sjödin, A., Cooper, D.A., Andréasson, K.J., (1995) Air Waste Manage. Assoc, 45, p. 186; Becker, K.H., Lörzer, J.C., Kurtenbach, R., Wiesen, P., Jensen, T.E., Wallington, T.J., (1999) Environ. Sci. Technol, 33, p. 4134; Taylor, K.C., (1993) Catal. Rev. Sci. Eng, 35 (4), p. 457; Gandhi, H.S., Shelef, M., (1991) Appl. Catal, 77, p. 175; Burch, R., Coleman, M.D., (1999) Appl. Catal. B: Environ, 23, p. 115; Burch, R., Breen, J.P., Meunier, F.C., (2002) Appl. Catal. B: Environ, 39, p. 283; Barrera, A., Viniegra, M., Bosch, P., Lara, V.H., Fuentes, S., (2001) Appl. Catal. B: Environ, 34, p. 97; Hilaire, S., Wang, X., Luo, T., Gorte, R.J., Wagner, P., (2001) Appl. Catal. A: General, 215, p. 271; Wang, X., Gorte, R.J., (2002) J. Catal, 224, p. 209","Fuentes, G.A.; Área de Ingeniería Química, Universidad A. Metropolitana-Iztapalapa, México, D.F., 09340, Mexico; email: gfuentes@xanum.uam.mx",,,,,,,,10225528,,TOCAF,,"English","Top. Catal.",Conference Paper,Scopus,2-s2.0-34347379181
